1
00:00:01,881 --> 00:00:03,881
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:01:06,761 --> 00:01:08,601
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

3
00:01:09,001 --> 00:01:11,961
Breathe slowly, son.
Well done, that's it.

4
00:01:14,041 --> 00:01:15,241
Well done.

5
00:01:16,521 --> 00:01:17,561
I'm alive.

6
00:01:19,401 --> 00:01:20,401
We are alive, right?

7
00:01:20,721 --> 00:01:22,201
As far as I can tell, yeah.

8
00:01:23,201 --> 00:01:25,361
(GROANS)

9
00:01:27,321 --> 00:01:28,401
Where are we?

10
00:01:28,801 --> 00:01:29,801
On a spaceship.

11
00:01:30,001 --> 00:01:31,601
WOMAN: My spaceship.

12
00:01:33,321 --> 00:01:34,321
Who's that?

13
00:01:34,401 --> 00:01:35,881
She says she's the pilot.

14
00:01:35,961 --> 00:01:37,121
We were in space.

15
00:01:37,801 --> 00:01:38,921
No way.

16
00:01:40,281 --> 00:01:43,561
We were in that warehouse and then,
we were in space.

17
00:01:43,641 --> 00:01:45,681
-Yeah.
-How were we in space?

18
00:01:46,001 --> 00:01:48,761
-I've got no idea.
-And why are we not in space now?

19
00:01:50,721 --> 00:01:54,801
I scooped you.
That was a very sneaky trick of his.

20
00:01:54,881 --> 00:01:56,841
Especially coming out of hyper jump.

21
00:01:56,921 --> 00:01:58,361
And you could've been killed.

22
00:02:00,041 --> 00:02:02,441
Listen, I keep telling you,

23
00:02:02,521 --> 00:02:04,601
we haven't got a clue
what you're talking about.

24
00:02:04,921 --> 00:02:06,201
Oh, have it your own way.

25
00:02:10,561 --> 00:02:11,761
Where in space are we?

26
00:02:11,841 --> 00:02:14,401
Just off the Final Planet,
which is out of orbit.

27
00:02:14,681 --> 00:02:17,641
Not where it should be.
But I still found it.

28
00:02:18,361 --> 00:02:21,081
What do you mean, "final planet"?
How can a planet be final?

29
00:02:21,161 --> 00:02:25,081
(CHUCKLING) You are
a very funny little bonus.

30
00:02:27,201 --> 00:02:28,361
Where's Yaz and the Doctor?

31
00:02:28,441 --> 00:02:31,081
-Are they here?
-No, I don't know where they are.

32
00:02:31,481 --> 00:02:33,041
I've been trying to get her
to look for them.

33
00:02:33,121 --> 00:02:34,921
I said there was four of us.

34
00:02:35,001 --> 00:02:37,121
And I said I only saw the two of you.

35
00:02:37,201 --> 00:02:40,441
I mean things were moving pretty fast,
speaking of which...

36
00:02:41,201 --> 00:02:43,521
Landing ahead.
Lock yourselves back in.

37
00:02:44,161 --> 00:02:45,241
We're not doing anything,

38
00:02:46,041 --> 00:02:48,881
unless you turn this thing around
and go and look for our friends.

39
00:02:48,961 --> 00:02:49,961
There'd be no point.

40
00:02:50,041 --> 00:02:51,961
If they were still there,
they'd be dead.

41
00:02:53,961 --> 00:02:55,121
They can't be dead.

42
00:02:55,801 --> 00:02:57,241
Don't panic. We'll figure it out.

43
00:02:57,681 --> 00:03:00,041
How? What happened to them?

44
00:03:01,401 --> 00:03:03,721
-(DOCTOR SHOUTING)
-(WHOOSHING)

45
00:03:03,801 --> 00:03:06,121
-(BEEPING)
-MAN: Stop insulting my ship.

46
00:03:06,201 --> 00:03:08,481
-This is one of the best crafts around!
-DOCTOR: I'd hate to see the others!

47
00:03:08,561 --> 00:03:10,721
MAN: I don't need your help.
DOCTOR: Yes you do.

48
00:03:10,801 --> 00:03:12,721
The power's failing
across three sections.

49
00:03:12,801 --> 00:03:14,681
This ship is on the verge
of total shutdown.

50
00:03:14,801 --> 00:03:16,601
How can a planet be in the wrong place?

51
00:03:16,681 --> 00:03:19,001
It should've been back there
where I scooped you up.

52
00:03:19,521 --> 00:03:21,121
We should be
in its gravity belt by now.

53
00:03:22,361 --> 00:03:24,121
-Well, we're not.
-I can see that.

54
00:03:24,201 --> 00:03:26,881
Hi. I can smell burning.

55
00:03:27,241 --> 00:03:28,921
You were right. She is still alive.

56
00:03:29,001 --> 00:03:30,801
Yaz, you need to stay locked
in the medipod.

57
00:03:30,881 --> 00:03:33,361
-Where's Ryan and Graham?
-There! The planet's there.

58
00:03:35,321 --> 00:03:36,801
How can it be there?

59
00:03:37,041 --> 00:03:38,121
Does it even have a name?

60
00:03:38,201 --> 00:03:41,841
Only a symbol. Or a warning.
Closest word is...

61
00:03:43,601 --> 00:03:44,721
Desolation.

62
00:03:45,961 --> 00:03:47,241
Right.

63
00:03:47,321 --> 00:03:49,601
I can do this.
I'm not going to be beaten. Move!

64
00:03:50,641 --> 00:03:52,041
I've still got a few tricks
up my sleeve.

65
00:03:53,481 --> 00:03:55,121
DOCTOR: Manual shield activation?

66
00:03:55,441 --> 00:03:57,481
Wow, this thing should be on
Antiques Roadshow.

67
00:03:57,561 --> 00:03:59,001
Right! Blast shield's up.

68
00:03:59,121 --> 00:04:00,761
Don't know how long
they'll last for though.

69
00:04:00,841 --> 00:04:03,681
Brilliant! We're about to crash-land on
Desolation. Real grounds for optimism.

70
00:04:03,761 --> 00:04:06,761
Do you not understand anything?
I can't even get us there.

71
00:04:07,001 --> 00:04:08,441
Because of the fuel I wasted...

72
00:04:08,681 --> 00:04:10,641
Because of the fuel I've wasted
scooping you up.

73
00:04:10,921 --> 00:04:13,601
I'm on a spaceship. Okay.

74
00:04:13,761 --> 00:04:17,321
I can get us into the atmosphere.
If we jettison the rear section.

75
00:04:17,401 --> 00:04:20,001
Listen to me.
Nobody is jettisoning anything.

76
00:04:20,081 --> 00:04:23,241
This is the Cerebos. All right?
She's the envy of millions.

77
00:04:23,841 --> 00:04:24,921
-Really?
-Yes.

78
00:04:25,001 --> 00:04:26,441
People have written songs about her.

79
00:04:26,521 --> 00:04:28,201
They'll be writing operas
about our pointless deaths

80
00:04:28,281 --> 00:04:30,321
if we don't take drastic action
right now.

81
00:04:31,241 --> 00:04:32,321
We're about to die?

82
00:04:32,401 --> 00:04:34,761
Oh, sorry, Yaz. I forgot you were there.
All gonna be fine.

83
00:04:35,441 --> 00:04:38,761
Five systems down!
Six minutes left on life support.

84
00:04:38,841 --> 00:04:40,281
Are we doing this or what?

85
00:04:43,081 --> 00:04:44,081
Oh, Rekk!

86
00:04:46,241 --> 00:04:47,361
Let's do it.

87
00:04:48,281 --> 00:04:49,641
Last stage anyway.

88
00:04:50,921 --> 00:04:51,921
-Catch.
-Ah!

89
00:04:53,321 --> 00:04:55,121
-And you.
-YASMIN: What's actually happening?

90
00:04:55,281 --> 00:04:56,401
DOCTOR: No need to panic, Yaz.

91
00:04:56,481 --> 00:04:58,361
We're just gonna blow the back
off this spaceship.

92
00:04:58,801 --> 00:05:00,401
-What?
-Jettisoning.

93
00:05:00,481 --> 00:05:02,601
-Do it.
-(RUMBLING)

94
00:05:04,001 --> 00:05:05,041
(MAN SCREAMING)

95
00:05:23,841 --> 00:05:25,881
RYAN: Whoa.
GRAHAM: I couldn't have put it better.

96
00:05:26,121 --> 00:05:27,241
RYAN: Hey!

97
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:29,361
Where are you going?

98
00:05:29,641 --> 00:05:31,721
I need to survey the atmospheric data.

99
00:05:32,441 --> 00:05:34,361
-We're on an alien planet, Graham.
-Yeah.

100
00:05:34,681 --> 00:05:37,441
Well, the three suns in the sky
are a bit of a giveaway.

101
00:05:38,081 --> 00:05:39,081
Uh-huh.

102
00:05:41,081 --> 00:05:42,161
What do we do?

103
00:05:45,161 --> 00:05:46,281
Should we just follow her?

104
00:05:47,081 --> 00:05:48,081
Yeah.

105
00:05:48,161 --> 00:05:50,521
Maybe they're already here.
Yaz and the Doctor.

106
00:05:50,601 --> 00:05:51,601
Maybe they're safe.

107
00:05:51,681 --> 00:05:53,481
All systems offline.
We're not gonna make it.

108
00:05:53,561 --> 00:05:55,321
Extra hand here.

109
00:05:57,401 --> 00:06:00,161
You can be honest with me.
Are we gonna die?

110
00:06:00,481 --> 00:06:02,881
One day, yes, comes to us all.

111
00:06:03,321 --> 00:06:06,081
But not right now.
Not if I've got anything to do with it.

112
00:06:06,161 --> 00:06:07,161
(MAN GRUNTING)

113
00:06:07,241 --> 00:06:09,121
This ship is old school.
I'm good at old school.

114
00:06:10,401 --> 00:06:13,641
Manual stabilisers.
Pull these two levers up,

115
00:06:13,921 --> 00:06:15,281
they'll pull down and to the left,

116
00:06:15,361 --> 00:06:17,761
pull them up and to the right
as strong as you can.

117
00:06:17,841 --> 00:06:18,841
Got it.

118
00:06:20,481 --> 00:06:21,961
That descent pattern won't work.

119
00:06:22,361 --> 00:06:24,441
We're about to die
and you're still having a go?

120
00:06:25,001 --> 00:06:26,041
Think you could do better?

121
00:06:27,401 --> 00:06:28,401
Yes!

122
00:06:29,681 --> 00:06:32,641
YASMIN: Doctor, these stabiliser
handles don't feel very stable.

123
00:06:32,721 --> 00:06:35,721
By the way, level-3 shield hazing.

124
00:06:35,961 --> 00:06:37,321
What? Seriously?

125
00:06:38,241 --> 00:06:41,441
Power failure.
We're headed into the gravity belt.

126
00:06:42,721 --> 00:06:45,361
Love, whoever you think we are,
we're not, all right?

127
00:06:45,521 --> 00:06:47,281
Are you still pleading ignorance?

128
00:06:48,161 --> 00:06:49,361
Do you guys hear that?

129
00:06:50,161 --> 00:06:53,041
Finskad! How did he even make it?

130
00:06:53,761 --> 00:06:55,201
It's another spaceship.

131
00:06:55,281 --> 00:06:57,161
Another spaceship about to crash-land.

132
00:06:57,441 --> 00:06:58,601
Oh!

133
00:06:58,841 --> 00:07:01,721
Don't just stand there. Run!

134
00:07:04,561 --> 00:07:06,921
It's coming. Run, run, run.

135
00:07:13,401 --> 00:07:14,721
(RYAN GRUNTS)

136
00:07:15,761 --> 00:07:17,241
(WIND HOWLING)

137
00:07:20,561 --> 00:07:21,841
Brace!

138
00:07:26,361 --> 00:07:27,681
(CRASHING)

139
00:07:34,361 --> 00:07:36,601
-RYAN: Doctor.
-Sorry about the mess.

140
00:07:37,521 --> 00:07:38,841
RYAN: Yaz, you're alive!

141
00:07:39,001 --> 00:07:40,121
We thought you were dead.

142
00:07:40,201 --> 00:07:41,441
We thought you were dead.

143
00:07:41,601 --> 00:07:42,761
Right. Quick update.

144
00:07:43,481 --> 00:07:45,601
I made a terrible mistake,
we shouldn't be here.

145
00:07:45,681 --> 00:07:47,881
I'm going to fix it
and get you guys home.

146
00:07:47,961 --> 00:07:48,961
I promise.

147
00:07:49,881 --> 00:07:52,401
-As soon I figure out where we are.
-How are you gonna do that?

148
00:07:52,801 --> 00:07:55,361
Not sure. Treating it as a chance
to surprise myself.

149
00:07:56,201 --> 00:07:57,921
Oh, by the way.
Welcome to what I presume

150
00:07:58,001 --> 00:08:00,201
is your first alien planet.
Don't touch anything.

151
00:08:00,481 --> 00:08:01,961
Come on, let's try this way.

152
00:08:02,761 --> 00:08:04,321
Look at you, Epzo.

153
00:08:05,201 --> 00:08:08,721
So you can't even control your own ship
now? You nearly killed us.

154
00:08:08,961 --> 00:08:10,801
Yeah, well I'll try harder
next time, eh?

155
00:08:12,321 --> 00:08:15,041
-Where's Kornlite and Fythen?
-Failed hyper jump.

156
00:08:16,281 --> 00:08:17,401
Both of them.

157
00:08:18,121 --> 00:08:19,241
It's just you and me left.

158
00:08:20,161 --> 00:08:21,441
You're kidding me.

159
00:08:23,401 --> 00:08:25,041
You have got so lucky.

160
00:08:25,641 --> 00:08:27,921
How did you even make it
this far, Angstrom, eh?

161
00:08:28,721 --> 00:08:29,921
You're nothing.

162
00:08:30,961 --> 00:08:33,401
Still, makes the next bit easy.

163
00:08:34,401 --> 00:08:37,601
(CHUCKLING) You would really love that,
wouldn't you?

164
00:08:38,521 --> 00:08:41,401
But I've got two bonuses. Same as you.

165
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:42,921
(ALARM SOUNDING)

166
00:08:43,001 --> 00:08:44,001
What's that?

167
00:08:44,081 --> 00:08:45,321
ANGSTROM: Here we go.

168
00:08:45,441 --> 00:08:47,361
DOCTOR: What do you mean, here we go?

169
00:08:47,641 --> 00:08:49,641
Here we go where? To what?

170
00:08:49,721 --> 00:08:51,521
RYAN: Yeah, where are we actually going?

171
00:08:51,601 --> 00:08:55,201
DOCTOR: Come on. Oh, I forgot
I put stuff in these pockets.

172
00:09:01,001 --> 00:09:03,481
GRAHAM: All this sand
is getting in my eyes something rotten.

173
00:09:03,801 --> 00:09:04,801
Want to borrow my shades?

174
00:09:04,961 --> 00:09:07,281
-Oh, ta!
-Like an old pair of mine.

175
00:09:07,361 --> 00:09:10,281
I say mine - can't remember
who I borrowed them off now.

176
00:09:11,201 --> 00:09:14,721
It was either Audrey Hepburn
or Pythagoras.

177
00:09:14,881 --> 00:09:16,561
Eh? Pythagoras never wore shades.

178
00:09:16,761 --> 00:09:19,041
Obviously never saw him with a hangover.

179
00:09:30,921 --> 00:09:32,521
Do you two know what that is?

180
00:09:34,201 --> 00:09:35,321
It's a tent.

181
00:09:35,401 --> 00:09:39,561
(TUTS) Obviously it's a tent.
I meant... Oh, never mind.

182
00:09:39,641 --> 00:09:41,161
Come on. No dawdling.

183
00:09:49,921 --> 00:09:51,081
Losers first.

184
00:09:58,881 --> 00:10:00,361
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

185
00:10:01,281 --> 00:10:04,241
Be careful.
I don't know what's going on.

186
00:10:04,321 --> 00:10:06,681
Could be dangerous.
Well, probably is dangerous.

187
00:10:07,561 --> 00:10:11,521
Can I ask if we are on an alien planet,
with aliens,

188
00:10:11,841 --> 00:10:13,961
how can we understand them?
Ain't they talking alien?

189
00:10:15,001 --> 00:10:18,081
Let's have a look. Yeah. Medipods
have put implants into each of you.

190
00:10:18,321 --> 00:10:19,841
Standard procedure.

191
00:10:20,241 --> 00:10:23,521
Checks for a universal translator.
Implants one if you don't have one.

192
00:10:23,721 --> 00:10:26,281
Eh? Well, can people and things

193
00:10:26,361 --> 00:10:28,401
stop putting stuff inside me
without my permission!

194
00:10:28,481 --> 00:10:30,601
If I had my TARDIS,
you wouldn't need them.

195
00:10:30,681 --> 00:10:32,001
Anyway, shall we?

196
00:10:47,801 --> 00:10:50,201
DOCTOR: This is lavish for a tent.

197
00:10:51,321 --> 00:10:53,761
I'm the Doctor.
These are my new best friends.

198
00:10:54,001 --> 00:10:55,841
Ryan, Graham, and Yaz. Now...

199
00:10:57,041 --> 00:10:58,361
(BUZZING)

200
00:10:58,441 --> 00:11:02,161
Ah, see. Hologram.
Thought it might be. Good one though.

201
00:11:02,241 --> 00:11:04,081
I love a good hologram.
I was a hologram once.

202
00:11:04,401 --> 00:11:06,281
For three weeks. The gossip I picked up.

203
00:11:06,601 --> 00:11:09,801
What are you?
Projection reality or Al interface?

204
00:11:10,401 --> 00:11:11,481
'Cause if you're interface,

205
00:11:12,361 --> 00:11:14,401
those are excellent nose hairs.

206
00:11:14,881 --> 00:11:15,961
Who are these people?

207
00:11:16,041 --> 00:11:17,481
-Bonuses.
-No.

208
00:11:18,081 --> 00:11:19,561
-What?
-I told you.

209
00:11:19,961 --> 00:11:21,721
Bonuses and snake traps are over.

210
00:11:21,801 --> 00:11:23,681
They were hanging in the star field
when we exited hyper.

211
00:11:23,761 --> 00:11:25,201
Are you saying
we scooped them for nothing?

212
00:11:25,281 --> 00:11:26,281
Yes.

213
00:11:26,361 --> 00:11:27,681
I sacrificed my ship.

214
00:11:27,761 --> 00:11:29,761
Yeah, sorry, some of this is my fault.

215
00:11:29,841 --> 00:11:33,401
Hi, we were loads of solar systems away,
I was trying to find my own ship,

216
00:11:33,481 --> 00:11:34,801
I got a fix on it here,

217
00:11:35,601 --> 00:11:37,561
and then it all went
quite badly wrong actually.

218
00:11:37,641 --> 00:11:40,001
These three have been very good
not going on about it.

219
00:11:40,081 --> 00:11:41,561
Very grateful you came along.

220
00:11:41,641 --> 00:11:43,641
Can I ask what is actually
going on here?

221
00:11:43,721 --> 00:11:46,001
-'Cause I'm confused. Are you confused?
-Pretty confused.

222
00:11:46,081 --> 00:11:48,321
-Proper confused.
-I'm way beyond confused.

223
00:11:48,681 --> 00:11:50,641
You are intruding on the final stage

224
00:11:50,721 --> 00:11:52,521
of the last ever
Rally Of The Twelve Galaxies.

225
00:11:52,601 --> 00:11:54,161
What, like, a race?

226
00:11:54,241 --> 00:11:57,681
Like Paris-Dhakar in space?
Are you two space-racing each other?

227
00:11:57,761 --> 00:11:58,761
We are the finalists.

228
00:11:58,841 --> 00:12:00,801
Four thousand entered. Two are left.

229
00:12:00,881 --> 00:12:02,561
Only one will claim the prize.

230
00:12:02,921 --> 00:12:04,921
-What's the prize?
-For the final ever race,

231
00:12:05,561 --> 00:12:07,601
three point two trillion krin.

232
00:12:07,681 --> 00:12:09,441
-Three point two trillion what?
-Krin.

233
00:12:09,521 --> 00:12:10,721
How much is a krin?

234
00:12:10,801 --> 00:12:12,681
-Two hundred kavlons.
-Ninety forvelars.

235
00:12:12,761 --> 00:12:14,561
-No.
-Four thousand trynties.

236
00:12:14,641 --> 00:12:17,121
-Oh, in old money.
-I'm a bit behind on my exchange rates,

237
00:12:17,201 --> 00:12:21,801
Enough to provide a lifetime
of comfort on a safe world

238
00:12:21,881 --> 00:12:24,081
for the winning pilot
and their entire clan.

239
00:12:24,161 --> 00:12:25,921
-Are we eligible too?
-No.

240
00:12:26,521 --> 00:12:29,241
You're irrelevant. Get on with it.
Tell us the task.

241
00:12:30,001 --> 00:12:32,761
Final challenge
is to cross the terrain,

242
00:12:33,121 --> 00:12:34,441
survive the planet.

243
00:12:34,921 --> 00:12:37,081
Make your way to the other side
of the mountains,

244
00:12:37,161 --> 00:12:39,521
and the first one
to get to the site marked

245
00:12:39,601 --> 00:12:42,561
as the Ghost Monument
will be crowned the winner.

246
00:12:42,641 --> 00:12:44,321
And transported off this planet.

247
00:12:44,801 --> 00:12:47,081
The loser will not.

248
00:12:47,241 --> 00:12:50,921
You can't leave one of us here.
The ships are out of fuel.

249
00:12:51,001 --> 00:12:53,841
Don't tell me what I can and cannot do
with my own race.

250
00:12:55,921 --> 00:12:58,041
You knew the risks when you joined.

251
00:13:00,961 --> 00:13:03,641
Biggest ever prize. Biggest ever risk.

252
00:13:04,561 --> 00:13:06,121
Wait. Hang on. What about us?

253
00:13:06,601 --> 00:13:08,761
Shut up. You're not part of this.

254
00:13:09,321 --> 00:13:13,121
Excuse me. We are human beings.
Show a bit of solidarity.

255
00:13:13,481 --> 00:13:15,721
I'm Muxteran, she's Albarian.

256
00:13:15,961 --> 00:13:17,881
Never even heard of Moomanbeans.

257
00:13:17,961 --> 00:13:20,361
Beings. Human beings. Earth.

258
00:13:20,441 --> 00:13:22,321
-No.
-Pretty cruel race.

259
00:13:22,961 --> 00:13:24,281
Leaving the loser stranded.

260
00:13:24,761 --> 00:13:28,721
The Rally is a test of survival.
How far will we go?

261
00:13:29,161 --> 00:13:32,761
How will we react when challenged?
It's the ultimate test.

262
00:13:32,961 --> 00:13:36,001
Interesting use of the word "we".
Seeing as though you're not here.

263
00:13:41,721 --> 00:13:43,721
Projected in from a very long way away.

264
00:13:44,361 --> 00:13:47,321
I started the Rally.
I competed, and I won.

265
00:13:47,401 --> 00:13:48,721
And now I'm going to end it.

266
00:13:49,001 --> 00:13:52,961
No sabotage, no injuries,
no killing each other.

267
00:13:53,041 --> 00:13:54,081
Shame.

268
00:13:54,161 --> 00:13:56,721
Instant disqualification applies.

269
00:13:58,361 --> 00:14:01,041
Now take your meds.
Don't travel at night.

270
00:14:01,281 --> 00:14:04,081
And don't drink the water.
In fact, don't even touch the water.

271
00:14:04,201 --> 00:14:06,601
This entire planet has been made cruel.

272
00:14:06,681 --> 00:14:08,881
Made cruel how? And by whom?

273
00:14:09,361 --> 00:14:11,241
This stage must be completed

274
00:14:11,921 --> 00:14:14,601
before one full solo rotation.

275
00:14:14,681 --> 00:14:17,521
You have one single piece of assistance.

276
00:14:19,641 --> 00:14:21,921
Transport. Provided by the water.

277
00:14:22,921 --> 00:14:25,361
Get across the water, through the ruins,

278
00:14:26,001 --> 00:14:29,721
and the site of the Ghost Monument
is on the other side of the mist swamps.

279
00:14:29,801 --> 00:14:30,801
Mist what?

280
00:14:30,881 --> 00:14:33,841
Your route trackers are over there.
Good luck.

281
00:14:34,001 --> 00:14:37,521
I know you prefer to ignore me,
but what is it? This Ghost Monument?

282
00:14:37,761 --> 00:14:40,001
The site was named
by the ancient settlers.

283
00:14:40,641 --> 00:14:43,921
It appears in exactly the same place
every thousand rotations.

284
00:14:44,321 --> 00:14:46,761
I've got my tracker. I'm good to go.

285
00:14:46,921 --> 00:14:48,401
See you for the prize, in.

286
00:14:48,481 --> 00:14:52,281
Finally get to light my Althusian cigar.
Saving it for the win.

287
00:14:54,881 --> 00:14:57,121
What does it look like? This monument?

288
00:14:57,401 --> 00:14:59,841
-What does it matter?
-Look at us.

289
00:15:00,361 --> 00:15:02,241
Four people who barely know each other,

290
00:15:02,321 --> 00:15:05,561
stranded on a planet called Desolation,
no route trackers,

291
00:15:05,641 --> 00:15:07,641
no way off, and judging by
what you've just told us,

292
00:15:07,721 --> 00:15:10,601
very little hope of survival.
I need all the information I can get.

293
00:15:10,841 --> 00:15:12,761
Including, but not limited to,

294
00:15:12,841 --> 00:15:16,161
what this Ghost Monument
actually looks like when it appears.

295
00:15:24,801 --> 00:15:26,281
-That's an old police box.
-Yeah.

296
00:15:26,841 --> 00:15:28,401
Yeah, like the one on Surrey Street.

297
00:15:28,481 --> 00:15:30,001
Only the one in town's green.

298
00:15:31,201 --> 00:15:32,361
This don't make any sense.

299
00:15:33,321 --> 00:15:34,881
It makes sense to me.

300
00:15:36,121 --> 00:15:38,161
Oh, thank you. Thank you so much.

301
00:15:39,681 --> 00:15:40,721
That'll do.

302
00:15:41,881 --> 00:15:43,961
Well, I'm sorry
I can't be of any more help.

303
00:15:44,641 --> 00:15:45,801
I don't think you are.

304
00:15:46,521 --> 00:15:47,561
You're right.

305
00:15:50,561 --> 00:15:51,801
Oh, bye, then.

306
00:15:51,921 --> 00:15:53,201
He was a bit full of himself.

307
00:15:53,281 --> 00:15:54,521
I've got a couple of questions.

308
00:15:54,601 --> 00:15:56,361
A couple? I got a book full.

309
00:15:56,641 --> 00:15:58,121
But shouldn't we keep with up
with those two

310
00:15:58,201 --> 00:15:59,441
before they get too far away?

311
00:15:59,521 --> 00:16:00,521
Yes.

312
00:16:01,481 --> 00:16:02,961
Now I know this is a bit of a shock.

313
00:16:03,041 --> 00:16:05,521
Well, you could say that.
I mean, we have been dumped in space.

314
00:16:05,601 --> 00:16:07,361
We got spaceships
crashing all around us.

315
00:16:07,441 --> 00:16:09,161
Now we are marooned on a planet

316
00:16:09,241 --> 00:16:11,161
that everyone else is racing
to get away from.

317
00:16:11,241 --> 00:16:13,041
All right.
Anyone can focus on the negatives.

318
00:16:13,121 --> 00:16:14,121
Well, what are the positives?

319
00:16:14,201 --> 00:16:18,601
What he called the Ghost Monument,
that's my ship. It's here.

320
00:16:18,801 --> 00:16:20,881
-What, the old police box?
-Didn't look all that.

321
00:16:21,041 --> 00:16:22,681
Its very "all that",
thank you very much.

322
00:16:22,761 --> 00:16:25,081
Don't you see, I got it mostly right.

323
00:16:25,481 --> 00:16:29,081
I tracked my TARDIS here,
but the planet had fallen out of orbit.

324
00:16:29,161 --> 00:16:31,401
We landed
where the planet should've been.

325
00:16:31,841 --> 00:16:34,201
It looks like the engines
are stuck in a loop.

326
00:16:34,641 --> 00:16:36,601
Phasing in and out of time and space.

327
00:16:37,681 --> 00:16:39,521
If we get to it when it phases in,

328
00:16:40,121 --> 00:16:43,001
I should be able to stabilise it,
then I can get you back home

329
00:16:43,081 --> 00:16:44,161
Definitely?

330
00:16:44,241 --> 00:16:46,441
If we get there,
you can get us off this planet alive?

331
00:16:46,521 --> 00:16:50,681
Yaz, I promise. I will keep you alive.
And I will get you back home.

332
00:16:51,041 --> 00:16:52,561
I'm really good in a tight spot.

333
00:16:53,041 --> 00:16:55,841
At least I have been historically.
I'm sure I still am.

334
00:16:56,121 --> 00:16:59,801
If we stick together, if you trust me,
we can get out of this.

335
00:16:59,881 --> 00:17:01,961
Right. Let's get a shift on.

336
00:17:06,841 --> 00:17:08,401
RYAN: Do you think
she's telling the truth?

337
00:17:09,361 --> 00:17:11,161
Do you really think
she can get us off here?

338
00:17:12,121 --> 00:17:15,081
YASMIN: She saved Karl.
She got the better of Tim Shaw.

339
00:17:15,601 --> 00:17:16,961
And she did jump a crane.

340
00:17:17,561 --> 00:17:19,921
Don't know what would've happened
if she hadn't have been there.

341
00:17:20,001 --> 00:17:22,801
Yaz is right.
I mean, she's our best hope,

342
00:17:23,121 --> 00:17:25,121
or only option
depending on your politics.

343
00:17:25,641 --> 00:17:26,641
Guess so.

344
00:17:27,001 --> 00:17:29,481
Don't argue with the wisdom
of Graham, eh?

345
00:17:30,361 --> 00:17:32,241
So we're sticking with Graham, are we,
and not Granddad?

346
00:17:33,401 --> 00:17:34,521
Yes, Graham.

347
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,841
EPZO: I said, stay away from the boat.

348
00:17:37,921 --> 00:17:39,441
ANGSTROM: You don't get this
to yourself.

349
00:17:39,561 --> 00:17:40,721
This blaster says I do.

350
00:17:40,801 --> 00:17:43,641
Put the blaster down.
We all know you're not gonna use it.

351
00:17:43,721 --> 00:17:46,361
No injuring, no killing, no sabotage.

352
00:17:46,481 --> 00:17:48,401
Isn't that what What-his-face said?

353
00:17:48,481 --> 00:17:50,441
Yeah, well,
maybe I don't play by the rules.

354
00:17:50,721 --> 00:17:52,441
Did you practise
those lines in the mirror?

355
00:17:53,161 --> 00:17:55,161
-See this?
-(GASPS)

356
00:17:55,441 --> 00:17:57,161
-Nice move.
-Thanks.

357
00:17:57,401 --> 00:18:00,361
Venusian Aikido.
Grand Master Pacifist.

358
00:18:00,641 --> 00:18:02,161
Temporarily paralyses,

359
00:18:02,241 --> 00:18:04,281
while also being fundamentally harmless.

360
00:18:04,441 --> 00:18:07,121
Very clever, those Venusian nuns.
Shall I let go?

361
00:18:07,961 --> 00:18:09,921
(GASPING AND COUGHING)

362
00:18:10,001 --> 00:18:11,481
ANGSTROM: And this boat doesn't work.

363
00:18:11,721 --> 00:18:14,321
-Oh, me and Ryan will take a look.
-Will we?

364
00:18:14,641 --> 00:18:16,801
Well, those NVQ classes
must be good for something.

365
00:18:16,881 --> 00:18:18,721
-An engine's an engine.
-Not a space engine.

366
00:18:19,161 --> 00:18:20,601
You don't get to take charge here.

367
00:18:20,721 --> 00:18:22,521
This is about me
and her fighting to win.

368
00:18:22,601 --> 00:18:25,561
We're all going to the same place and
that boat is big enough for all of us.

369
00:18:25,641 --> 00:18:28,441
Yaz is right. If we get it started,
we all get onboard.

370
00:18:28,561 --> 00:18:31,801
Yeah, I know what this is.
You are all part of Ilin's game.

371
00:18:32,801 --> 00:18:34,881
Saboteurs. Sent to throw us off.

372
00:18:35,041 --> 00:18:37,281
You think the whole universe
is out to get you.

373
00:18:37,801 --> 00:18:39,201
How's your family, Angstrom?

374
00:18:46,041 --> 00:18:47,921
So that's why he said
don't touch the water.

375
00:18:48,721 --> 00:18:51,721
Flesh eating microbes.
Millions of them living in there.

376
00:18:52,361 --> 00:18:54,441
Toxic atmosphere. Killer water.

377
00:18:55,561 --> 00:18:56,961
Very dangerous planet, Yaz.

378
00:19:03,561 --> 00:19:06,481
You were right.
Not like any engine I've ever seen.

379
00:19:13,041 --> 00:19:14,561
We ever gonna talk about your nan?

380
00:19:16,361 --> 00:19:18,561
I mean, just because all this
is going on,

381
00:19:18,641 --> 00:19:20,041
don't mean to say it didn't happen.

382
00:19:21,321 --> 00:19:23,001
See, I cope myself

383
00:19:23,401 --> 00:19:25,881
by asking the question "If Grace
was here what would she say?"

384
00:19:30,161 --> 00:19:31,281
What do you reckon?

385
00:19:32,121 --> 00:19:34,721
Well, right now she'd be going,
"What's the matter with you?

386
00:19:35,121 --> 00:19:36,881
"You're on another planet.
How cool is that?"

387
00:19:39,161 --> 00:19:40,281
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

388
00:19:41,841 --> 00:19:43,161
And it is. Right?

389
00:19:44,521 --> 00:19:47,281
-I'm gonna look out for you, son.
-I'm not a kid.

390
00:19:49,001 --> 00:19:50,081
Well, okay.

391
00:19:50,761 --> 00:19:53,681
Well, I was hoping you'd say,
"I'm gonna look out for you, too".

392
00:19:55,241 --> 00:19:57,961
-You talk about this stuff way too much.
-Mmm-hmm.

393
00:20:02,441 --> 00:20:04,041
And you don't talk about it enough.

394
00:20:06,841 --> 00:20:09,761
That's not an engine.
That's more like a massive battery.

395
00:20:11,921 --> 00:20:14,081
-What if it's solar?
-Look at you boys.

396
00:20:14,801 --> 00:20:16,961
Light years from home.
Figuring things out.

397
00:20:18,401 --> 00:20:20,321
Yep, three suns in the sky.

398
00:20:21,281 --> 00:20:24,321
Tri-solar engineering panels
on the outside powering that battery.

399
00:20:24,601 --> 00:20:27,201
Well, if it won't start,
maybe the panels aren't lined up.

400
00:20:27,601 --> 00:20:29,521
Or maybe they're not feeding
the battery properly.

401
00:20:29,881 --> 00:20:31,001
Loving your work, boys.

402
00:20:31,481 --> 00:20:32,761
Let's take a look.

403
00:20:34,201 --> 00:20:35,921
I've never seen so much water.

404
00:20:37,361 --> 00:20:38,801
You're Albarian, he said?

405
00:20:39,761 --> 00:20:42,321
Yes, the planet of Albar.

406
00:20:43,761 --> 00:20:45,321
It's tiny.

407
00:20:45,401 --> 00:20:47,401
Crammed full of rusting high-rises.

408
00:20:48,361 --> 00:20:51,441
Everyone wants to leave
any way they can. Even more so since...

409
00:20:53,241 --> 00:20:54,321
Since what?

410
00:20:57,321 --> 00:20:58,641
I don't know you.

411
00:21:00,321 --> 00:21:02,521
Up and running. All aboard.

412
00:21:08,721 --> 00:21:09,961
Hey, Yaz, can you believe it?

413
00:21:10,721 --> 00:21:12,161
Alien planet, man.

414
00:21:12,801 --> 00:21:13,881
I know.

415
00:21:14,121 --> 00:21:15,801
This planet doesn't make any sense.

416
00:21:15,881 --> 00:21:18,361
No other life forms except us
and the microbes in the water.

417
00:21:18,441 --> 00:21:21,841
No people, no animals,
no insects, no nothing.

418
00:21:22,561 --> 00:21:24,441
But he talked about the old settlements.

419
00:21:24,841 --> 00:21:26,001
What happened here?

420
00:21:26,521 --> 00:21:27,681
No one cares.

421
00:21:28,841 --> 00:21:30,281
ANGSTROM: Don't take him personally.

422
00:21:31,201 --> 00:21:32,481
He treats everyone like this.

423
00:21:35,161 --> 00:21:36,481
I don't need other people.

424
00:21:38,121 --> 00:21:39,441
We all need other people, mate.

425
00:21:39,841 --> 00:21:41,001
We're all alone.

426
00:21:42,001 --> 00:21:43,681
That's how we start and end.

427
00:21:43,761 --> 00:21:46,001
And it's the natural state
of all points in between.

428
00:21:46,081 --> 00:21:48,401
Were you born that miserable?
Or did you have to work at it?

429
00:21:48,481 --> 00:21:49,681
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

430
00:21:53,041 --> 00:21:56,801
You know, when I was four,
my mum told me to climb a tree.

431
00:21:57,561 --> 00:21:59,961
She made me climb until I was too scared
to climb any higher.

432
00:22:00,801 --> 00:22:03,121
Then she told me to jump into her arms.

433
00:22:04,641 --> 00:22:08,561
"Don't worry,"” she said. "I'm your mum.
I'm here for you. I'll catch you."

434
00:22:10,761 --> 00:22:11,961
So I jumped.

435
00:22:14,121 --> 00:22:15,361
And she moved out of the way.

436
00:22:16,121 --> 00:22:17,161
What?

437
00:22:18,041 --> 00:22:20,361
Sorry.
Did you say your mum did this to you?

438
00:22:21,081 --> 00:22:22,201
Smashed into the ground.

439
00:22:22,441 --> 00:22:24,721
Broke this arm. Shattered that ankle.

440
00:22:25,321 --> 00:22:27,961
And she stood over me, and she said,
"Now, you've learned.

441
00:22:29,721 --> 00:22:31,921
"You can never trust anyone
in this life. "

442
00:22:33,801 --> 00:22:34,921
That is messed up.

443
00:22:35,001 --> 00:22:36,281
Best thing she ever did for me.

444
00:22:38,601 --> 00:22:39,681
I loved my mum.

445
00:22:39,841 --> 00:22:41,281
Yeah, she sounds terrific.

446
00:22:44,481 --> 00:22:45,481
Your mum was wrong.

447
00:22:46,681 --> 00:22:47,761
We're stronger together.

448
00:22:59,481 --> 00:23:02,761
I see your mate's dropped off.
It's nice to see him quiet.

449
00:23:02,881 --> 00:23:03,961
Yeah.

450
00:23:04,041 --> 00:23:06,001
He can nap anywhere. Famous for it.

451
00:23:07,561 --> 00:23:09,121
How many stages are there in the rally?

452
00:23:09,361 --> 00:23:13,241
This time? 209 terrains, 94 planets.

453
00:23:13,801 --> 00:23:16,561
We start the race with nothing
and barter our way up.

454
00:23:16,641 --> 00:23:17,641
Is it worth it?

455
00:23:18,121 --> 00:23:21,561
To ensure enough
for my family's safety? Yeah.

456
00:23:22,601 --> 00:23:24,961
Albar is being systematically cleansed.

457
00:23:26,761 --> 00:23:28,641
Half my family are in hiding.

458
00:23:29,641 --> 00:23:31,001
The others are on the run.

459
00:23:33,361 --> 00:23:36,401
This is my only chance
to bring us back together.

460
00:23:36,481 --> 00:23:38,161
So you left your family to do this?

461
00:23:38,281 --> 00:23:41,001
I left my family
to try and save my family.

462
00:23:41,081 --> 00:23:42,161
They told me to.

463
00:23:42,761 --> 00:23:45,041
If I win, I find them.

464
00:23:46,001 --> 00:23:47,201
Rescue them.

465
00:23:49,721 --> 00:23:51,001
If they're alive to be rescued.

466
00:23:53,041 --> 00:23:54,161
And whatever happens here,

467
00:23:54,721 --> 00:23:56,921
it's a better chance
than I have back home.

468
00:23:57,001 --> 00:23:58,401
You're making me miss my family.

469
00:23:59,401 --> 00:24:00,921
That's quite some achievement.

470
00:24:01,961 --> 00:24:03,401
Considering my dad drives me bananas,

471
00:24:03,521 --> 00:24:06,201
and my sister's trying to get me
to move out so she can have my bedroom.

472
00:24:07,681 --> 00:24:08,881
And I only saw them yesterday.

473
00:24:09,761 --> 00:24:11,601
Don't ever take them for granted.

474
00:24:16,761 --> 00:24:18,441
Oh, you all look shattered.

475
00:24:19,521 --> 00:24:21,801
You should all rest.
I'll wake you when we get there.

476
00:24:35,761 --> 00:24:36,801
Ryan.

477
00:24:39,841 --> 00:24:41,521
Ryan. Wake up, son.

478
00:24:43,961 --> 00:24:46,201
I'm awake. I'm awake.

479
00:24:47,601 --> 00:24:48,881
Are we home?

480
00:24:48,961 --> 00:24:51,201
No. Time to get off the boat. Come on.

481
00:24:54,481 --> 00:24:56,721
ANGSTROM: Have you seen yourself, Epzo?

482
00:24:57,161 --> 00:25:01,401
I'd say you love that cigar
more than you've loved any person.

483
00:25:01,561 --> 00:25:04,841
Have you any idea how rare
and expensive these are?

484
00:25:05,841 --> 00:25:08,641
Takes half an Althusian lifetime
to make just one of these.

485
00:25:09,001 --> 00:25:10,841
To make them, roll them,

486
00:25:11,441 --> 00:25:13,321
age them, and then,
and this is the best bit,

487
00:25:14,201 --> 00:25:15,681
they make them self-lighting.

488
00:25:16,281 --> 00:25:17,921
Just one click of the finger

489
00:25:18,001 --> 00:25:19,681
and it lights itself.

490
00:25:21,201 --> 00:25:22,681
You want a sniff?

491
00:25:22,761 --> 00:25:24,121
Closest you'll ever get to victory.

492
00:25:24,241 --> 00:25:25,761
It's bad for your health.

493
00:25:28,041 --> 00:25:30,721
ANGSTROM: Big set of ruins.
DOCTOR: Wonder who those were built for.

494
00:25:30,961 --> 00:25:32,081
EPZO: Why do you even care?

495
00:25:32,681 --> 00:25:33,921
Where are those people now?

496
00:25:35,241 --> 00:25:38,721
And why are there so few signs of life?
What happened to everyone?

497
00:25:39,001 --> 00:25:40,001
Bye.

498
00:25:40,361 --> 00:25:41,561
Good luck.

499
00:25:42,241 --> 00:25:43,681
EPZO: You're already lost, Angstrom.

500
00:25:45,561 --> 00:25:47,241
GRAHAM: What, we're just
letting them go, are we?

501
00:25:47,321 --> 00:25:48,921
How do we know what to do? Where to go?

502
00:25:49,041 --> 00:25:51,801
First thing we have to do is make it
through those ruins safely.

503
00:25:52,001 --> 00:25:54,641
Because these readings are all over
the place and I don't know why.

504
00:26:00,961 --> 00:26:02,001
(PANTING)

505
00:26:04,321 --> 00:26:05,801
(MECHANICAL BUZZING)

506
00:26:10,121 --> 00:26:11,441
(BEEPING)

507
00:26:15,521 --> 00:26:16,721
(BEEPING)

508
00:26:24,361 --> 00:26:26,321
DOCTOR: Those suns are starting to set.

509
00:26:26,521 --> 00:26:28,961
They're moving
way faster than I realised.

510
00:26:29,041 --> 00:26:32,761
Well, back in the tent that bloke Ilin
said, "Do not travel by night."

511
00:26:32,841 --> 00:26:34,761
We need to move. Fast.

512
00:26:37,881 --> 00:26:39,681
GRAHAM: Whoa! They weren't there
when we came in.

513
00:26:39,761 --> 00:26:41,081
RYAN: Where did they come from?

514
00:26:41,161 --> 00:26:42,241
DOCTOR: I don't know.

515
00:26:43,041 --> 00:26:44,321
YASMIN: Oh, my God! Doctor!

516
00:26:45,201 --> 00:26:47,361
So much for no life forms
on this planet.

517
00:26:47,441 --> 00:26:50,201
They're not alive. They're robot guards.

518
00:26:50,481 --> 00:26:52,881
Why would you need robot guards
on a deserted planet?

519
00:26:58,881 --> 00:27:00,601
Good news is they're not fully active.

520
00:27:00,721 --> 00:27:05,281
So what we all need to do is
very slowly, totally unthreateningly,

521
00:27:05,721 --> 00:27:07,401
back out of here.

522
00:27:07,921 --> 00:27:09,081
-(WEAPON FIRING)
-(GRUNTS)

523
00:27:11,081 --> 00:27:12,841
DOCTOR: They've been activated. Run!

524
00:27:13,361 --> 00:27:15,121
GRAHAM: Move, move, everyone. Come on.

525
00:27:17,561 --> 00:27:18,801
DOCTOR: Ahhh... Ha...

526
00:27:20,401 --> 00:27:23,001
Don't run straight.
They're predicting your path.

527
00:27:30,001 --> 00:27:32,281
Move! In here.

528
00:27:38,081 --> 00:27:40,001
Well done, all of you. Nice running.

529
00:27:40,721 --> 00:27:43,361
(GASPS) Oh! Okay. Come on.

530
00:27:44,641 --> 00:27:46,401
Oh! What have we here?

531
00:27:50,641 --> 00:27:52,241
YASMIN: Have you got
anything there, Doctor?

532
00:27:53,201 --> 00:27:55,881
Information. Oh! That's bad.

533
00:27:57,281 --> 00:27:58,521
They're SniperBots.

534
00:27:59,801 --> 00:28:02,081
We just walked
into the middle of the shooting range.

535
00:28:02,201 --> 00:28:04,801
Everything within the perimeter
is target practice.

536
00:28:05,281 --> 00:28:07,081
Which would explain
all the targets in here.

537
00:28:07,161 --> 00:28:08,601
And looking on the negative side,

538
00:28:09,921 --> 00:28:11,161
they're human-shaped targets.

539
00:28:11,561 --> 00:28:13,721
If that's the way it is,
time to stop messing about.

540
00:28:13,841 --> 00:28:15,321
-What are you doing?
-Fighting back.

541
00:28:15,441 --> 00:28:17,641
No. Guns, never use them.

542
00:28:17,721 --> 00:28:19,001
-They're shooting at us.
-I know.

543
00:28:19,081 --> 00:28:20,281
They're gonna kill us with their guns.

544
00:28:20,361 --> 00:28:21,401
He's got a point, Doc.

545
00:28:21,521 --> 00:28:23,761
-Put the gun down, Ryan.
-What's your better idea?

546
00:28:24,161 --> 00:28:26,201
-Out-think them.
-You can't out-think bullets.

547
00:28:26,281 --> 00:28:29,081
-I've been doing it all my life.
-Uh-uh. Sorry.

548
00:28:29,681 --> 00:28:32,281
Call of Duty, man.
I've trained for this.

549
00:28:33,481 --> 00:28:34,721
(YELLING)

550
00:28:34,801 --> 00:28:35,961
(WEAPON FIRING)

551
00:28:38,281 --> 00:28:39,281
Who's next?

552
00:28:40,081 --> 00:28:42,761
See, that's what I'm talking about.
That's how you deal with things.

553
00:28:43,161 --> 00:28:45,121
Taking out the aliens!

554
00:28:45,321 --> 00:28:47,201
No. No. Where's the reload?

555
00:28:47,681 --> 00:28:50,041
Where's the reload?
Where's the reload?

556
00:28:50,121 --> 00:28:51,961
(SCREAMING)

557
00:28:52,041 --> 00:28:54,121
(SNIPERBOTS' WEAPONS FIRING)

558
00:28:54,201 --> 00:28:56,521
-Made it worse?
-Just a little bit, yeah.

559
00:28:56,601 --> 00:28:58,041
Now do you see why I don't like guns?

560
00:28:58,121 --> 00:29:00,441
-Don't go on about it.
-I will go on about it. A lot.

561
00:29:00,881 --> 00:29:02,561
-DOCTOR: They're here.
-(WEAPON WHIRRING)

562
00:29:02,841 --> 00:29:04,441
Take cover. Behind the pillars.

563
00:29:06,281 --> 00:29:07,721
YASMIN: You know we're
completely surrounded.

564
00:29:07,841 --> 00:29:09,681
-Yep.
-GRAHAM: With no way out whatsoever.

565
00:29:10,481 --> 00:29:13,681
Here's a lesson.
The answer was on the floor.

566
00:29:13,761 --> 00:29:15,681
You just reached for the wrong thing.

567
00:29:15,801 --> 00:29:17,161
GRAHAM: What're you talking about?

568
00:29:17,241 --> 00:29:18,841
DOCTOR: The best thing about robots is

569
00:29:19,441 --> 00:29:22,441
they're powerful.
Literally packed with power.

570
00:29:23,161 --> 00:29:24,681
Super-powered.

571
00:29:25,161 --> 00:29:26,161
(BEEPING)

572
00:29:26,241 --> 00:29:27,401
(BOOMING)

573
00:29:31,721 --> 00:29:33,681
Okay, now that was impressive.

574
00:29:33,961 --> 00:29:35,521
Thank you. I aim to please.

575
00:29:36,561 --> 00:29:38,081
What exactly did you just do?

576
00:29:38,401 --> 00:29:39,921
Electromagnetic pulse.

577
00:29:40,441 --> 00:29:41,761
Basically fried their systems.

578
00:29:42,081 --> 00:29:44,601
I reckon we've got about five minutes
before they reboot and recover.

579
00:29:45,201 --> 00:29:47,201
See? Brains beat bullets.

580
00:29:47,281 --> 00:29:48,681
Come on.

581
00:29:54,201 --> 00:29:56,761
-(GROANING)
-Epzo. Is that you?

582
00:29:57,961 --> 00:29:59,961
-Oh, my God! What happened?
-(GRUNTING)

583
00:30:04,161 --> 00:30:06,721
-Do you need help?
-Not from you.

584
00:30:07,561 --> 00:30:09,241
DOCTOR: Let's try through here.

585
00:30:11,241 --> 00:30:12,521
EPZO: What just happened?

586
00:30:12,601 --> 00:30:14,321
What do you care?
You don't care about anything.

587
00:30:14,881 --> 00:30:17,841
-Oh, tracker. Thanks.
-How did you even do that?

588
00:30:18,521 --> 00:30:21,041
Did I not mention? I am really smart.

589
00:30:21,481 --> 00:30:22,481
Thank you.

590
00:30:22,561 --> 00:30:23,881
You are very welcome.

591
00:30:23,961 --> 00:30:25,681
Amazing what you can learn
from a SniperBot.

592
00:30:25,761 --> 00:30:27,881
Like where their control commands
emanate from.

593
00:30:28,081 --> 00:30:29,681
Also, maps.

594
00:30:32,081 --> 00:30:33,721
Which leads us...

595
00:30:34,801 --> 00:30:36,041
here.

596
00:30:38,041 --> 00:30:39,201
(WHEEL GRINDING)

597
00:30:41,961 --> 00:30:44,681
I want answers to this planet
and I think they're down there.

598
00:30:44,761 --> 00:30:45,961
You sure about that?

599
00:30:46,081 --> 00:30:48,241
No. Come on.

600
00:30:53,961 --> 00:30:55,121
(EXHALES)

601
00:30:55,961 --> 00:30:57,401
Why is it always ladders ?

602
00:31:07,041 --> 00:31:09,161
See? Second nature now.

603
00:31:09,241 --> 00:31:10,721
No, not really.

604
00:31:11,481 --> 00:31:12,721
Thanks for waiting.

605
00:31:13,041 --> 00:31:14,121
Always.

606
00:31:14,281 --> 00:31:16,961
DOCTOR: These tunnels
run under half of the planet.

607
00:31:17,041 --> 00:31:18,201
Think of the technology,

608
00:31:18,281 --> 00:31:20,361
the civilisation required
to build all that.

609
00:31:20,481 --> 00:31:23,121
Then ask yourselves where are they?

610
00:31:23,761 --> 00:31:25,801
-(EPZO GROANS)
-How's the injury?

611
00:31:25,881 --> 00:31:27,361
It's painful.

612
00:31:27,441 --> 00:31:29,801
I hope it's made you reconsider
your entire philosophy.

613
00:31:30,201 --> 00:31:31,281
No.

614
00:31:31,521 --> 00:31:32,561
GRAHAM: Doctor.

615
00:31:35,961 --> 00:31:37,601
Scorch marks all along the walls.

616
00:31:38,601 --> 00:31:40,681
Not exactly encouraging, is it?

617
00:31:40,761 --> 00:31:43,481
-No.
-Still, best feet forward.

618
00:31:50,161 --> 00:31:52,801
Big locked door.
I love a big locked door.

619
00:31:54,201 --> 00:31:55,601
(ZAPPING, DOOR OPENS)

620
00:31:58,081 --> 00:31:59,401
Ominous.

621
00:32:11,281 --> 00:32:12,561
DOCTOR: What happened in here?

622
00:32:17,641 --> 00:32:18,921
There's another room next door.

623
00:32:21,601 --> 00:32:23,401
-We'll take a look?
-Yeah.

624
00:32:25,481 --> 00:32:27,321
I don't wanna be here.

625
00:32:27,401 --> 00:32:29,441
We're off route. We need to move on.

626
00:32:29,521 --> 00:32:31,401
You went into the ruins
without knowing what was there.

627
00:32:31,761 --> 00:32:34,121
You want to keep going without knowing
why it's bad to travel at night?

628
00:32:34,441 --> 00:32:36,241
Whatever happened here is in the past.

629
00:32:36,361 --> 00:32:37,681
What does it matter to you?

630
00:32:37,761 --> 00:32:39,961
This was a living,
breathing planet once.

631
00:32:40,441 --> 00:32:44,201
With an ecosystem, organic life,
and a population.

632
00:32:44,281 --> 00:32:46,641
There was a catastrophic event here.

633
00:32:47,361 --> 00:32:48,801
And as hard as it is
for you to understand,

634
00:32:48,881 --> 00:32:50,681
you are not the only life form
in this universe.

635
00:32:51,041 --> 00:32:54,121
Some of us feel a duty
to others who might be in trouble.

636
00:32:54,481 --> 00:32:57,641
So fix your wound,
take one of your heroic naps,

637
00:32:57,721 --> 00:32:59,961
and we'll wake you when we leave,
if you're lucky.

638
00:33:01,081 --> 00:33:02,361
Fine.

639
00:33:05,921 --> 00:33:07,561
Now, do me a favour,

640
00:33:08,441 --> 00:33:10,921
give me something that will finally
make sense of this planet.

641
00:33:18,721 --> 00:33:19,721
(EPZO GROANS)

642
00:33:20,321 --> 00:33:21,561
(HISSING)

643
00:33:22,601 --> 00:33:24,481
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

644
00:33:27,001 --> 00:33:28,281
That's more like it.

645
00:33:28,921 --> 00:33:31,081
Angstrom, throw me
that route-mappy thing.

646
00:33:34,841 --> 00:33:36,041
If we sync it,

647
00:33:37,161 --> 00:33:39,921
it shows us
the whole network of tunnels.

648
00:33:40,361 --> 00:33:42,361
Your friend Ilin warned us
not to travel at night.

649
00:33:42,441 --> 00:33:44,721
We could use the tunnels
to keep moving while it's dark,

650
00:33:44,921 --> 00:33:46,881
avoiding whatever's on the surface.

651
00:33:47,641 --> 00:33:49,921
It's better than that, look.

652
00:33:50,001 --> 00:33:51,961
There's the site of the Ghost Monument.

653
00:33:52,441 --> 00:33:55,001
This network could help us
cut a diagonal through the route.

654
00:33:55,081 --> 00:33:57,201
Then bypass
most of the mountain terrain.

655
00:33:57,321 --> 00:33:58,961
We could cover the distance
in half the time.

656
00:33:59,401 --> 00:34:00,801
Well, if you leave now,

657
00:34:00,881 --> 00:34:02,921
you could get there
before Sleeping Beauty.

658
00:34:03,001 --> 00:34:04,201
You could win.

659
00:34:07,401 --> 00:34:08,601
GRAHAM: What was that?

660
00:34:09,641 --> 00:34:11,401
DOCTOR: There's something
through there.

661
00:34:12,521 --> 00:34:15,401
YASMIN: Ryan, have you seen this?
Surveillance footage.

662
00:34:16,001 --> 00:34:18,281
RYAN: Look, they found the hatch.

663
00:34:26,161 --> 00:34:27,841
DOCTOR: Inscriptions on the floor.

664
00:34:28,001 --> 00:34:29,761
What is it?
Some sort of cave painting?

665
00:34:29,881 --> 00:34:30,921
Almost.

666
00:34:31,121 --> 00:34:32,721
Left by the people who worked here.

667
00:34:33,401 --> 00:34:35,321
Can you read it? What does it say?

668
00:34:37,841 --> 00:34:39,121
"We are scientists,

669
00:34:40,921 --> 00:34:45,121
"abducted, tortured, and made to work,

670
00:34:45,521 --> 00:34:47,361
"while our families are held hostage.

671
00:34:48,761 --> 00:34:51,641
"We are forced to find
new ways of destruction.

672
00:34:53,881 --> 00:34:55,201
"Poisons,

673
00:34:55,961 --> 00:34:58,241
"weapons, creatures.

674
00:34:59,321 --> 00:35:01,081
"We gave them our minds,

675
00:35:01,761 --> 00:35:04,041
"and they made us the creators of death.

676
00:35:05,961 --> 00:35:09,921
"This planet has been left scorched
and barren from our work.

677
00:35:10,001 --> 00:35:12,721
"The atmosphere and water are toxic.

678
00:35:13,921 --> 00:35:16,841
"Killing machines and creatures
inhabit every corner.

679
00:35:17,881 --> 00:35:21,281
"We had no choice but to obey...

680
00:35:26,521 --> 00:35:27,841
"...the Stenza.

681
00:35:29,041 --> 00:35:31,721
"We are trying to destroy
all of our work

682
00:35:32,081 --> 00:35:34,081
"before they use it against others."”

683
00:35:36,281 --> 00:35:38,281
There's two words below that.

684
00:35:39,361 --> 00:35:40,921
"They're coming."

685
00:35:42,201 --> 00:35:43,201
That's how it ends.

686
00:35:44,281 --> 00:35:45,441
The Stenza?

687
00:35:45,521 --> 00:35:47,921
That's the thing we stopped
in Sheffield, right?

688
00:35:49,321 --> 00:35:50,721
You know the Stenza too?

689
00:35:52,641 --> 00:35:54,601
My wife died because of them.

690
00:35:56,001 --> 00:35:57,361
Mine, too.

691
00:35:59,721 --> 00:36:00,921
I'm sorry.

692
00:36:03,281 --> 00:36:04,521
They took our planet.

693
00:36:05,721 --> 00:36:08,121
Sent us into hiding.
Cleansed millions of us.

694
00:36:11,681 --> 00:36:13,321
(FAINT CHANTING)

695
00:36:14,401 --> 00:36:17,081
(EERIE WOOSHING AND WHISPERING)

696
00:36:24,641 --> 00:36:25,881
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

697
00:36:28,521 --> 00:36:29,801
DOCTOR: Epzo!

698
00:36:31,881 --> 00:36:33,321
GRAHAM: Oh, my God.

699
00:36:34,201 --> 00:36:36,481
DOCTOR: Nothing's working on it.

700
00:36:40,121 --> 00:36:41,881
Doc, we've seen them before.

701
00:36:42,001 --> 00:36:44,161
Like all over the planet,
like they were lying dormant.

702
00:36:44,641 --> 00:36:47,561
Lying dormant till night.
Across the whole planet.

703
00:36:48,281 --> 00:36:49,761
Clearing up the wounded.

704
00:36:49,841 --> 00:36:52,961
Doctor, I've found you. The SniperBots
are on their way down after us!

705
00:36:54,641 --> 00:36:56,921
We need to get out of here.
Everybody move fast!

706
00:37:13,281 --> 00:37:14,761
(ELECTRIC WHIRRING)

707
00:37:24,121 --> 00:37:26,121
YASMIN: Why have we stopped?

708
00:37:27,241 --> 00:37:28,921
DOCTOR: Listen...

709
00:37:29,561 --> 00:37:32,561
They've shut down the life-support
systems, depriving us of air.

710
00:37:34,441 --> 00:37:36,441
A man could really
take against those robots.

711
00:37:37,401 --> 00:37:39,121
We need to get out of the tunnels.

712
00:37:39,201 --> 00:37:40,281
It's night.

713
00:37:40,361 --> 00:37:43,361
This exit ladder will take us
up and out to the surface.

714
00:37:44,281 --> 00:37:45,441
What's up there?

715
00:37:46,321 --> 00:37:48,201
Acetylene fields.

716
00:37:48,281 --> 00:37:49,881
Acetylene? Like the gas?

717
00:37:49,961 --> 00:37:52,761
That doesn't sound good.
We're running out of air and options.

718
00:37:52,841 --> 00:37:54,361
So let's go up.

719
00:37:55,961 --> 00:37:58,001
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

720
00:38:00,121 --> 00:38:01,601
(GRAHAM GRUNTS)

721
00:38:05,801 --> 00:38:07,241
DOCTOR: You okay?

722
00:38:08,881 --> 00:38:10,121
It's not my favourite thing.

723
00:38:11,561 --> 00:38:12,961
Climbing ladders under pressure.

724
00:38:13,921 --> 00:38:16,161
Can I just say? You are amazing.

725
00:38:16,241 --> 00:38:17,241
Am I?

726
00:38:17,321 --> 00:38:19,041
Think of what you've gone through
to be here.

727
00:38:19,121 --> 00:38:21,121
And you're still going.
I'm proper impressed.

728
00:38:21,361 --> 00:38:22,401
Thanks.

729
00:38:23,041 --> 00:38:26,241
If it helps, focus on facts
about acetylene as you climb.

730
00:38:26,881 --> 00:38:28,321
Did you cover it in NVQ?

731
00:38:28,401 --> 00:38:30,041
I think I might have done, yeah.

732
00:38:30,121 --> 00:38:32,281
Gotta be quick now, Ryan. Sorry.

733
00:38:32,441 --> 00:38:33,601
(EXHALES)

734
00:38:36,361 --> 00:38:37,841
YASMIN: That's some smell.

735
00:38:37,921 --> 00:38:40,321
GRAHAM: What is it, garlic?
RYAN: Wait. Everyone stop.

736
00:38:40,401 --> 00:38:42,561
Look. It's like the ground's moving.

737
00:38:42,961 --> 00:38:44,801
(WHOOSHING)

738
00:38:44,881 --> 00:38:48,361
WHISPERING VOICE:
Finally, a big feast of life...

739
00:38:49,241 --> 00:38:50,401
DOCTOR: Nobody move.

740
00:38:50,481 --> 00:38:53,121
EPZO: Don't let them touch you,
they'll squeeze the life out of you.

741
00:38:53,321 --> 00:38:57,001
Yes, squeeze the life from all of you.

742
00:38:57,761 --> 00:38:59,681
The talk is to distract you.

743
00:38:59,761 --> 00:39:01,761
That's how they were designed
in that laboratory.

744
00:39:01,841 --> 00:39:05,441
You can't save them.
We smell your fear, too.

745
00:39:05,561 --> 00:39:07,561
The strongest of all.

746
00:39:07,641 --> 00:39:10,521
You want fears?
I've got a dozen lifetimes' worth.

747
00:39:10,601 --> 00:39:13,401
A dozen lives? We'll take you first.

748
00:39:13,481 --> 00:39:14,961
You remember any facts, Ryan?

749
00:39:15,761 --> 00:39:17,161
As we climbed?

750
00:39:18,761 --> 00:39:20,081
It's lighter than air?

751
00:39:20,361 --> 00:39:24,681
Yes. It smells like garlic
and lighter than air. That's right.

752
00:39:25,401 --> 00:39:26,681
And one other thing about it.

753
00:39:27,401 --> 00:39:29,681
But we'll all have to dig deep
for that, right?

754
00:39:29,761 --> 00:39:31,521
What are you talking about?
What are you doing?

755
00:39:31,601 --> 00:39:33,001
Shut up, and dig, Epzo.

756
00:39:33,081 --> 00:39:37,481
You lead but you're scared too,
for yourself and for others.

757
00:39:37,561 --> 00:39:40,161
Yeah, well. Who isn't?

758
00:39:40,241 --> 00:39:42,161
Afraid of your own newness.

759
00:39:42,241 --> 00:39:45,361
We see deeper, though, further back.

760
00:39:45,441 --> 00:39:47,321
The Timeless Child.

761
00:39:48,481 --> 00:39:49,561
What did you just say?

762
00:39:49,721 --> 00:39:51,201
She doesn't know.

763
00:39:51,281 --> 00:39:52,521
What are you talking about?

764
00:39:53,881 --> 00:39:54,881
What can you see?

765
00:39:55,121 --> 00:39:58,281
We see what's hidden,
even from yourself.

766
00:39:58,441 --> 00:40:01,921
The outcast abandoned and unknown.

767
00:40:03,801 --> 00:40:05,041
Get out of my head.

768
00:40:05,161 --> 00:40:08,801
Now we crush those fears from you.

769
00:40:08,881 --> 00:40:11,321
Enjoy your feast. Whatever it is.

770
00:40:11,481 --> 00:40:14,121
You know what some people
like after a feast?

771
00:40:14,241 --> 00:40:16,201
-Graham.
-Huh?

772
00:40:16,361 --> 00:40:18,201
Not me. Some people.

773
00:40:20,361 --> 00:40:21,601
EPZO: Do it.

774
00:40:21,681 --> 00:40:24,321
Oh, yeah. A nice cigar.

775
00:40:26,201 --> 00:40:27,921
-DOCTOR: Down!
-(YASMIN SCREAMS)

776
00:40:37,201 --> 00:40:38,561
Third fact -

777
00:40:38,681 --> 00:40:41,241
ignites very easily.

778
00:40:41,721 --> 00:40:43,041
Good old acetylene.

779
00:40:43,201 --> 00:40:45,361
See? Teamwork.

780
00:40:46,401 --> 00:40:48,281
Now, move. Come on.

781
00:41:02,921 --> 00:41:04,201
RYAN: We must be near now.

782
00:41:04,321 --> 00:41:05,521
Says we're close.

783
00:41:08,041 --> 00:41:10,241
There. Your finish line.

784
00:41:10,641 --> 00:41:12,201
EPZO: Ah! We made it.

785
00:41:14,321 --> 00:41:17,281
But where's your ship?
Where's the Ghost Monument?

786
00:41:17,361 --> 00:41:18,481
It's not here.

787
00:41:19,921 --> 00:41:21,081
I don't understand.

788
00:41:23,961 --> 00:41:25,681
It should be here.

789
00:41:25,761 --> 00:41:27,481
We did all this for nothing.

790
00:41:30,681 --> 00:41:32,121
So you got here.

791
00:41:33,921 --> 00:41:36,241
And now I'm going to claim my prize.

792
00:41:36,881 --> 00:41:39,001
What? Your prize?

793
00:41:40,001 --> 00:41:43,121
I saved your life.
You'd be dead without me.

794
00:41:43,481 --> 00:41:46,641
And if I raced you now to that tent,
you'd be dust.

795
00:41:47,441 --> 00:41:49,081
You're a wreck, Epzo.

796
00:41:51,281 --> 00:41:53,561
Who had the cigar, eh?

797
00:41:54,161 --> 00:41:56,121
Me. That was mine.

798
00:41:56,521 --> 00:41:59,001
-The cigar saved us all.
-Seriously?

799
00:42:00,201 --> 00:42:02,961
Don't even think
I'm going to lose to you now.

800
00:42:03,681 --> 00:42:05,801
DOCTOR: Er, can I make a suggestion?

801
00:42:09,761 --> 00:42:11,721
-Dead heat.
-ANGSTROM: Joint first.

802
00:42:12,201 --> 00:42:13,681
Dual winners.

803
00:42:13,761 --> 00:42:15,241
With witnesses.

804
00:42:15,321 --> 00:42:17,401
What? No.

805
00:42:17,481 --> 00:42:20,041
There's never been a joint winner
of the Rally.

806
00:42:20,121 --> 00:42:21,841
-There has now.
-No.

807
00:42:22,841 --> 00:42:26,121
I will declare the final race
null and void.

808
00:42:29,641 --> 00:42:32,681
Ilin, you've made this
a living hell for us.

809
00:42:33,921 --> 00:42:37,561
I promise you that whatever happens,
I will get off this planet.

810
00:42:38,081 --> 00:42:39,841
And if we don't get what
we both fought for,

811
00:42:39,921 --> 00:42:41,241
I will hunt you down,

812
00:42:41,321 --> 00:42:43,121
and ensure that whatever time
you have left

813
00:42:43,201 --> 00:42:45,881
is both short-lived and agonising.

814
00:42:46,961 --> 00:42:48,801
Do we understand each other?

815
00:42:49,681 --> 00:42:51,201
Now,

816
00:42:51,281 --> 00:42:52,801
recognise your equal winners.

817
00:42:54,481 --> 00:42:57,321
Pay the prize or pay the price.

818
00:43:01,001 --> 00:43:04,361
I'm honoured to declare
a unique joint victory.

819
00:43:05,681 --> 00:43:07,161
An equal split.

820
00:43:09,241 --> 00:43:12,321
Now, get us off this rock.

821
00:43:12,401 --> 00:43:13,401
Fine.

822
00:43:13,481 --> 00:43:15,281
-And them.
-No.

823
00:43:15,361 --> 00:43:16,681
ANGSTROM: No!

824
00:43:23,881 --> 00:43:25,121
They're gone?

825
00:43:30,841 --> 00:43:32,041
We're stuck here, are we?

826
00:43:36,441 --> 00:43:37,561
I'm sorry.

827
00:43:39,001 --> 00:43:40,241
I failed you.

828
00:43:43,681 --> 00:43:45,521
I promised you and I let you down.

829
00:43:51,801 --> 00:43:53,601
We can wait, can't we?

830
00:43:55,001 --> 00:43:57,201
Yeah. We've got each other.

831
00:43:58,281 --> 00:44:00,001
No, we'll be dead within one rotation.

832
00:44:03,281 --> 00:44:06,081
Who says so?
We've come this far, haven't we?

833
00:44:07,921 --> 00:44:09,481
Who says we're giving up? Any of us?

834
00:44:10,361 --> 00:44:12,001
Really? Even you, Doc?

835
00:44:13,001 --> 00:44:15,281
No, come on,
we ain't having that, are we?

836
00:44:15,521 --> 00:44:16,801
-Nope.
-No.

837
00:44:17,641 --> 00:44:19,241
(FAINT WHOOSHING)

838
00:44:21,401 --> 00:44:22,921
Can you hear that noise?

839
00:44:30,361 --> 00:44:31,881
Come on, please.

840
00:44:32,361 --> 00:44:33,521
Give us this.

841
00:44:36,241 --> 00:44:38,961
It's all right. It's me.

842
00:44:40,281 --> 00:44:41,441
Stabilise.

843
00:44:43,081 --> 00:44:44,201
Come to Daddy.

844
00:44:44,641 --> 00:44:45,801
I mean Mummy.

845
00:44:45,921 --> 00:44:48,641
I mean, I really need you right now.

846
00:44:50,201 --> 00:44:51,521
(WHOOSHING)

847
00:44:56,481 --> 00:44:58,361
My beautiful Ghost Monument.

848
00:45:09,521 --> 00:45:12,481
Hello you. I've missed you.

849
00:45:14,561 --> 00:45:15,761
Oh!

850
00:45:17,201 --> 00:45:18,921
You've done yourself up!

851
00:45:22,441 --> 00:45:23,441
Very nice.

852
00:45:26,841 --> 00:45:28,521
I've lost my key.

853
00:45:28,601 --> 00:45:30,281
Sorry.

854
00:45:33,241 --> 00:45:34,481
But it's an old police box.

855
00:45:36,721 --> 00:45:38,681
Sort of. Not really.

856
00:45:39,161 --> 00:45:40,881
You expect us all to fit inside there?

857
00:45:41,401 --> 00:45:43,361
-Yep.
-At the same time?

858
00:45:44,121 --> 00:45:46,241
-Wanna try?
-RYAN: Okay.

859
00:45:46,801 --> 00:45:49,401
Oh, word of warning.
I left it in a bit of a mess.

860
00:45:56,641 --> 00:45:57,761
Oh!

861
00:45:59,281 --> 00:46:00,801
You've redecorated.

862
00:46:37,281 --> 00:46:38,921
I really like it.

863
00:46:46,921 --> 00:46:48,641
This is my TARDIS.

864
00:46:50,081 --> 00:46:51,201
Wow.

865
00:46:52,361 --> 00:46:53,481
Yeah.

866
00:46:55,041 --> 00:46:56,401
It was a police box.

867
00:46:56,481 --> 00:46:58,201
It still is on the outside.

868
00:46:58,281 --> 00:47:02,121
How do you fit all this stuff
inside a police box?

869
00:47:02,961 --> 00:47:04,441
Dimensional engineering.

870
00:47:05,481 --> 00:47:07,881
-You can't engineer dimensions.
-Maybe you can't.

871
00:47:08,041 --> 00:47:09,401
-Can I press any of...
-No.

872
00:47:10,001 --> 00:47:11,241
It's a spaceship?

873
00:47:12,161 --> 00:47:13,481
And a times hip.

874
00:47:14,201 --> 00:47:15,801
-Get out.
-Seriously.

875
00:47:17,121 --> 00:47:20,761
This is proper...awesome.

876
00:47:20,841 --> 00:47:23,081
I thought maybe you didn't believe me
that I'd get you home.

877
00:47:23,161 --> 00:47:25,521
I thought you didn't believe yourself
for a second back there.

878
00:47:25,601 --> 00:47:28,281
Who me? No. Never doubted.

879
00:47:28,361 --> 00:47:29,601
Don't know what you mean.

880
00:47:29,961 --> 00:47:31,361
Home then?

881
00:47:31,801 --> 00:47:34,281
You can get us there? Really?

882
00:47:34,841 --> 00:47:36,401
Start believing.

883
00:47:42,401 --> 00:47:43,761
(RUMBLING)

884
00:47:51,001 --> 00:47:52,481
(WHOOSHING)

885
00:47:52,561 --> 00:47:53,601
(GASPS)

886
00:48:05,201 --> 00:48:06,921
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

887
00:48:35,161 --> 00:48:37,001
DOCTOR: 1955, Montgomery, Alabama.

888
00:48:38,001 --> 00:48:40,001
Parks, Rosa Parks.

889
00:48:40,081 --> 00:48:41,281
No way!

890
00:48:41,361 --> 00:48:42,761
RYAN: If she can live here all her life,

891
00:48:42,841 --> 00:48:44,561
a couple of hours ain't gonna kill me.

